<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-11-21T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-11-21T23:00:00-05:00" n="727" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d727">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/1418: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-11-22T12:00:00+08:00">November 22,
                                1936—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received November 22—10 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>565. Following telegram has been sent to Shanghai: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“November 22, noon. Your 604, November 21, 4 p.m. I agree with
                                    your views in this matter and approve action you and British
                                    Consul General propose to take. I believe also that secrecy
                                    should be combated.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>